##Day and night in the Golden Pool Hospital

Since the first patient was admitted, the hospital has been overloaded for nearly two months. Doctors, nurses, patients, volunteers, are working around the clock for the new coronavirus. A mixture of despair and hope, gloom and lucidity, bitterness and emotion, enveloped Wuhan.

Since the first patient was admitted, the hospital has been overloaded for nearly two months. Doctors, nurses, patients, volunteers, are working around the clock for the new coronavirus. A mixture of despair and hope, gloom and lucidity, bitterness and emotion, enveloped Wuhan.

7,410 words, about 14 minutes to read

Click on the image below to read the Hsinking special report

HSINKING, Wang Shuangxing, Liang Jingyi, Han Ruxue, Zu Yifei, Wang Feixiang, Wei Furong, editor, Hu Jie, proofread, Wu Xingfa

During the plasmapheresis, Zhang Chunyan, a nurse in the ICU, stayed with the patient for more than three hours.

The young man in the hospital bed was 29 years old. Earlier, he had told Zhang Chunyan that his wife was pregnant and he was going to be a father. But now the young father-to-be is getting sicker.

Zhang stood by and watched as 40 bags of 50 ml of plasma trickled into the patient's body with the Catheter, a blood purification treatment that doctors hoped would buy him more time.

In the Golden Pool Hospital, such treatment and rescue are carried out every day. As a designated hospital for medical treatment of public health emergencies in Wuhan and the first group of designated hospitals for new coronary pneumonia patients, the hospital represents the treatment trend of the national new coronary pneumonia to a certain extent. The WORD ON THE STREET: The World Sees China, China sees Hubei, Hubei Sees Wuhan, Wuhan sees a lake of gold and silver.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital. Photo by Wang Feixiang, reporter of Beijing News

As of February 10, more than 1,500 new cases of pneumonia had been admitted to the hospital and more than 500 patients had been discharged, Zhang Dingyu, director of Wuhan's Golden Pond Hospital, said in an interview with the media, the cumulative cure discharge rate of the hospital has exceeded 43% .



A young nurse writes a suicide note on the day of the city closure

January 23, Wuhan "closed" that day, Lin Zhenzhen to write their own "suicide note.

Now in her fourth year, she is 26 years old and has worked as a nurse at Golden Pond Hospital since she graduated.

On the same day that a nurse in Lin's department contracted new pneumonia, a intensive-care unit director and a doctor at the hospital were also attacked. Lin found his colleagues in low spirits. Someone in the Department wrote a suicide note. She also wrote, the Bank Card Password and the purchase contract of the House together, gave the sister. "I didn't dare tell my parents directly, for fear they wouldn't be able to bear it. "

The hospital has 685 health professionals and technicians, according to its website. As an Infectious Disease Hospital specializing in public health matters in Wuhan, Kam Yin Tam Hospital was the first designated hospital to admit new pneumonia patients after the outbreak. Later, other hospitals opened and a shelter hospital was built, critical patients are still being transferred to Golden Pool Hospital.

In the past, Lin Zhenzhen department work load, often busy to "homesick mother also want to cry, " but compared to today's work, suddenly feel "tired before not worth mentioning.

A number of medical and nursing staff in the Jinyintan hospital recalled that in late January, the Huoshenshan and Rayshenshan hospitals had not yet been completed, and the domestic medical teams had not yet arrived in large numbers. The hospital was at the stage of receiving a large number of patients, especially those with confirmed severe cases, and most chaotic period of time.

"At the beginning all the pneumonia patients were put together, did not follow the quarantine requirements, that is, a ward is full, light and heavy all put together, not separate. "

At the same time, patients began to deteriorate. "Four or five liters didn't work, either 40 or 50 liters, or it was aspirated. Some people couldn't do it in the ward, and then they were intubated in the ICU, " recalls a nurse who has worked for years at the Golden Pool Hospital, since admitting patients with new coronary pneumonia, she has observed that these patients breathe in oxygen of 4 liters and 5 liters or more, which is a very high oxygen intake. As a first-line paramedic, I've never seen anything like this before.

As the outbreak spread, more and more patients were admitted to the hospital, and part of the wards were temporarily converted into intensive-care unit. From January 17, the team of Tongji Hospital stayed in the South Building of Jinyintan Hospital, 7 floors of the Department of Critical Medicine; Wuhan People's Hospital and Xiehe Hospital were responsible for transforming 6 floors and 5 floors into ICU respectively.

Yu Zhui, deputy director of the Department of Critical Care Medicine at the People's Hospital, told the media that starting from January 19, the six-floor Ward has been treating critical patients while completing the transformation, "The ICU requires very professional equipment. At the beginning of the reconstruction, there were many supporting facilities that could not keep up. There were no monitors, suction machines, infusion pumps and so on

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 13, medical staff in the ICU of Wuhan Jinyintan hospital looked at the patient's physical condition. Changjiang daily, by Chen Zhuo

Zhang Chunyan, a nurse at intensive-care unit in Hunan Province, has been supporting Wuhan since Jan. 27, recalling the early chaos, "A lot of nurses don't work in intensive-care unit, " she said. "They can't use it, and they can't do blood purification. It's like putting a duck on a shelf. "

Zhang Chunyan recalls that at first, because of limited supplies, some nurses did not have face screens and only wore goggles and masks to care for patients.

At that time, the restraints tied to the patients were also made by the nurses themselves. During the intubation, some patients felt uncomfortable and struggled with great strength. Once the restraints broke directly, Zhang Chunyan ran to hold the hands of the patients, until the doctor can re-intubate.

Compared with other hospitals, as a Special Infectious Disease Hospital, Jinyintan hospital has a relatively sufficient reserve of protective materials, but at the same time, because most of the critically ill patients in Jinyintan hospital centralized treatment, materials began to appear gaps.

Zheng Junhua, the first group leader of the shanghai-hubei medical team, told the media that at that time Jinyintan hospital had only 500 sets of protective isolation clothing, only enough to use for two days.

Wei Ming, a department director at Jinyintan Hospital, told CCTV on Jan. 26 that she was facing a shortage of supplies.

"Our biggest worry is that we don't have enough protective materials, so we won't have N95 masks the day after tomorrow... " halfway through, Wei ming-hong blinked, sheepishly waved his hand and turned his head to one side.

Wei Ming, whose department has only 4 doctors, began working round the clock on the 20th and did not have a normal rest for 6 days. If you can't wait for protection, it's only going to get harder.

"Happy New Year" was whispered on the plane

January 24th, New Year's Eve.

When the Lunar New Year arrived, Lin Zhenzhen's department received express delivery of dumplings, cakes, flowers. Colleagues sent over to call Lin Zhenzhen eat together, she realized that the New Year. In the past, mom at home will make dumplings, spring rolls, according to the original plan, Lin Zhenzhen intended to bring his boyfriend home to meet his parents this Spring Festival.

The bell sounded, Shanghai University of Chinese Medicine Affiliated Longhua Hospital breathing nurse Zhen Wei and colleagues are headed to Wuhan on the plane. As one of the first 135 members of the Shanghai medical team, she didn't have time to eat a Chinese New Year dinner in just a few hours from 5:30 p.m. , when she was told to get on the plane. Night filled outside the cabin, at midnight, she and the side of the team with the support of Ordos gently said: "Happy New Year. ".

The South sixth floor of the White Building in the Golden Pool Hospital is a u-shaped intensive care unit.

Here, most are 50 to 70-year-old seriously ill patients, in addition to routine care, nurses also responsible for patients'life care, injection, medicine, suction, feeding, care of stool and urine, blood purification.

Zhang Chunyan and his colleagues work on the fifth, sixth and seventh floors of the South Tower, where the most critical patients are treated.

Zhang Chunyan is mainly responsible for the blood purification treatment, commonly known as "Blood Dialysis" , which exports the blood of critically ill patients, relies on treatment equipment to remove the inflammatory factors therein, and then reinfuses the clean blood into the patient's body to slow down the progress of the disease, to buy more time for treatment and reduce the case fatality rate.

For the first time, she had so much protection: Four layers of clothing, including close fitting clothing, work clothes, isolation clothing, waterproof clothing; two layers of masks, N95 masks plus general surgical masks; and three layers of surgical gloves.

On his first day at work, Zhang took on six patients, twice as many as before, working 11 hours a day and cleaning up after work as the hospital lacked cleanup workers, zhang Chunyan and her colleagues needed to tie up the garbage bags themselves. "For the first few days, it was [ exhausting ] to the point of collapse. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A doctor wears protective equipment before entering a negative pressure ward at Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital on February 13. Changjiang daily, by Chen Zhuo

Some nurses recalled that not only did life care add to the workload, but routine care also seemed to strain under the weight of protection. "For example, the simple infusion, wearing several layers of gloves, eye goggles in the fog. (blood vessels) is not easy to touch, can not see clearly, and wearing protective clothing is very boring, some patients joke: You nurses even more than we breathe. "

Zhang Chunyan a colleague once told the media: (and partner) did not know before, you speak that point, the other party may not know. For example, in the rescue, who is responsible for pressing, who is responsible for spraying, who will record the rescue time, who ordered, a team of people should be very clear division of Labor. But now everyone is wearing protective clothing, no one knows each other, you just came here, you don't know where the rescue supplies are, and you have to call for help, but other people have to take care of six or seven patients, and their own patients may not be in very good condition. It's a lot of pressure to do these things in a panic and blindly.

Fortunately, on the 10th day of the work, there were more and more support teams. Zhang Chunyan's team had medical personnel from Fujian, Anhui and other places. A team of seven people gathered from all corners of the country, zhang Chunyan's job was a little easier.

On the afternoon of February 17, the Medical Surveillance Commissioner of the State Health Commission said that more than 32,000 medical personnel, mainly from the specialties of inhalation, infection and severe illness, had been sent to support Wuhan, Hubei Province.

Hospital beds were added along with medical staff. On January 26, the Army Medical University medical team moved into Jinyintan Hospital and completed the renovation of the hospital's general ward building, adding 96 beds, CCTV reported. As of February 17, there were 811 beds in the hospital.

I can't see your face, but I can remember your voice

January 26, the second day of the Lunar New Year.

In the afternoon, the Shanghai medical team officially took over the two wards of Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, which are located on the second and third floors of the North building and have about 80 beds.

That day, Dr. Frankie Ng and his colleagues finished rounds. "It just feels heavier than it is, there are more serious patients than it is, and basically the vast majority of ICU patients are on suction support. "

The main idea, Frankie Ng says, is to provide supportive care according to the treatment plan, so that patients are not deprived of oxygen.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A doctor measures a patient in an isolation ward at Oxygenation in Wuhan on Feb. 13. Changjiang daily, by Chen Zhuo

In addition, because viral pneumonia pneumonia is viral pneumonia, doctors will treat patients with antiviral drug and, if there are co existing bacterial infections, increase the use of antibiotics, as appropriate.

On weekdays, patients can bring their cell phones into the ICU. Frankie Ng was impressed by a 65 year old woman. She would call her daughter as soon as she felt up to it, but she was getting sicker and Sicker, and despite all the treatment the doctors were giving her, she had no strength left to hold the phone. Even so, "I kept my phone close at hand, " Frankie Ng said. "She told me that she wanted to get better and take care of her granddaughter, that her daughter was struggling at work and that she was worried that she wouldn't be able to take care of the baby. "

Talking to each other, Frankie Ng says, also feels like talking to your parents. So I kept reassuring her that it was okay, that I would get out of the hospital, that I would get home early, and I would see my granddaughter, and I would see my daughter.

But the disease continued to accelerate, and three weeks after Frankie Ng took over, the old man died. "The whole process of deterioration is particularly unpleasant. "

Over time, Frankie Ng became more and more moved by the idea that each patient had a family behind him, and that a patient's safe release from the hospital might change the family's fate, and vice versa.

On the front lines, a sense of powerlessness alternates with hope in the minds of medical staff.

The 29-year-old father-to-be, who was treated for blood purification by Zhang Chunyan, was admitted to the hospital on January 30. His name is Peng Yinhua. He is Zhang Chunyan's patient and a colleague. Prior to his illness, the First People's Hospital of Jiangxia District / Concord Jiangnan Hospital had been breathing and critically ill medical doctors in the front line of Epidemic Prevention.

Zhang Chunyan originally thought, February 19 plasma replacement, also for Peng Yinhua bit by bit into the hope of rehabilitation, "we all hope he quickly good. ". But at 9:50 p.m. on the 20th, news of his death came.

This sort of thing happens, from time to time, in the early days of aid. Zhang Chunyan said he had taken care of an infected male nurse, who was obese and in his 50s and could not breathe, "every time I saw him, it was hard to breathe in, and sometimes when I stood next to him, I could only hold his hand and comfort him. "Fortunately, over the past few days, the male nurse's performance has gradually improved. And every bit of information that a patient is getting better brings great hope to health care workers.

Zhen Wei, 38, has been working as a nurse for 16 years. "relatively speaking, I have seen more life and death, " she said. However, when she first arrived at the ward, she still found it hard to accept. On the first day, the patient was still optimistic, but the next day she could not breathe, "Why did so much change happen overnight? " Zhen said, adding that many patients "are actually younger than me, and it's really hard to see such patients walking down such a road. "

Qian Xiao, a nurse from the intensive-care unit in Shanghai Sixth People's Hospital, has been taking care of a 61 year old grandmother. When Qian first entered the ward, she was under a lot of pressure, but as soon as they met, the grandmother said to her, "I'm not afraid of you and I'm not afraid of you. I'm going to listen to the doctors and I'm going to cooperate with you. "

On February 20, grandma was discharged from the hospital. In fact, Qian Xiao wore a mask every time she attended the hospital. Grandma could only see her big eyes. But that day, grandma took Qian Xiao's hand and spoke for 20 minutes. "I can't see your face clearly, but I can remember your voice, " she said. Qian nearly cried, but she choked it off, "I couldn't cry because I couldn't see clearly with the fog on my face. " But it was 3:40 p.m. , Ms. Qian recalled, when the soft sunlight streamed through the window. "I felt the sunshine in Wuhan for the first time. It was so beautiful. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 13, Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, the South third floor isolation ward director in ward rounds, and patient exchanges. Changjiang daily, by Chen Zhuo

His hair was all down, on his scalp, all sweaty

On the morning of January 30, Zhang Chunyan cut her long chestnut-colored hair, which she had spent more than 800 yuan to dye just before the Spring Festival, because it needed to be washed twice a day and was difficult to manage. She had a dior 999 lipstick and hadn't used it for over a month because she was always wearing a mask.

While the doctors and nurses were busy day and night in the ward, the staff of the Treasure Pool First Aid station were on the way all the time.

On December 29,2019, Jinyintan first aid station received instructions to "transfer some patients with pneumonia of unknown origin" to Jinyintan Hospital; since the 31st, there has been a transfer of similar patients; later, the number of new coronary pneumonia cases began to increase in January 2020.

The Wuhan Emergency Centre has 57 first aid stations throughout the city. After the outbreak, other stations are responsible for transporting people to the Emergency Department of the hospital, while the Kam Yin Tam station is mainly responsible for transporting confirmed cases.

The equipment is also different from most first aid stations. The two ambulances in the Golden Pool are negative-pressure vehicles, which can minimize the risk of cross-infection among medical staff and discharge the air from the vehicles after a harmless treatment.

After the city was sealed off, the number of patients increased and the two ambulances in the station began to work at the same time.

"It's equivalent to working 48 hours to get a day off, but if there are other tasks on the day off, like carrying supplies and so on, people are going to do them, " said Li Fei, a first aid worker.

When there are many confirmed cases that need to be transferred, each negative pressure cart has to hold five to eight patients, Li Fei said, which tests the ability of medical staff to handle them.

Transfer to the hospital, most of the serious cases, in the car to ensure that each patient has sufficient oxygen points. Li Fei says there will be two more portable tanks, which can be used to give oxygen to other patients, except those who need it badly.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On February 20, dozens of empty oxygen cylinders were waiting to be pulled out of their cans. Photograph by Wang Feixiang, Hsinking Daily News

In order to meet the needs of multiple patients at the same time, colleagues also use transfusion tee connected to the nasal oxygen tube, "transformation" out of the multi-head oxygen interface.

Before transporting the patients, we need to check their names, ages, check case records, imaging data, and so on. We also need to make a preliminary assessment of their condition to ensure the safety of the patients in transit. After transporting the patients to Jinyintan Hospital, we need to transport the patients to the ward, "In the hands of the doctor on duty. ".

A lot of times, it takes six or seven hours to get down. "before many colleagues went to work, they had to blow their hair out, but now it's all hanging down, sticking to their scalp, all sweaty. "

After the outbreak, not only Jinyintan first-aid station, the entire Wuhan 57 first-aid Station Emergency Personnel and nearly 100 ambulances, to three or four times the daily workload began to rush. Wuhan's emergency services used to get about 3,000 calls a day. Today, there are more than 10,000, up from 15,000. When there are many patients, at least 600 people who call 120 a day have to wait in line, according to a staff member at the emergency center.

At its peak, Dr. Li Fei said, the number of patients transferred to the hospital within 24 hours was "more than a hundred, or dozens more, " and more recently, it was "mainly patients transferred from the shelter hospital, " with fewer patients. Li Fei and his colleagues, who used to sleep only two or three hours a day during their busiest days, are taking longer breaks.

"Fruit, yogurt, jerky... lots and lots of it. "

On February 20, there was complete silence in the hospital. Apart from the hurried medical staff, there was hardly anyone else in the compound.

Chen Nian, a nurse, had just come out of her ward with more than 20 mild cases and 10 more seriously ill patients who needed constant attention. Compared with the cold and cheerless in the hospital, the ward was as busy as ever. The number of newly diagnosed cases of pneumonia in Wuhan dropped from four to three, but "the ward is still full" .

In early February, the Vulcan Mountain Hospital and the Thor Mountain Hospital were built and put into use one after another, dispersing the pressure of designated hospitals such as gold and Silver Lake.

Construction of the Shelter Hospital started on February 3. Twelve shelter hospitals have been fully opened in Wuhan, with more than 20,000 beds planned for the city, Xinhua reported on February 19.

On February 5, the new pneumonia epidemic prevention and control headquarters in Hubei Province issued an order requiring that suspected and confirmed cases be "collected and treated with all possible treatment. ". By mid February, health care workers were beginning to sense a decline in patient numbers.

Another change is the strengthening of supplies. Jinyintan hospital medical supplies emergency news out, the community from all walks of life donated materials continue to pour here.

In addition to the usual protective materials, a wide variety of living materials were brought in. "Fruit, yogurt, beef Jerky, Ginseng Lozenges, even Haidilao Hotpot, down jackets, Long Johns, many, many more. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
February 13, Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital, lunchtime, north fourth floor doctors in the hospital logistics department to receive the sick meal. Changjiang daily, by Chen Zhuo

Volunteer Hu Yifan witnessed the hospital materials from tension to ease. The day before the "city closure" , he joined the Wuhan anti-epidemic Volunteer Union. At that time, the feeling is that almost every hospital is in a hurry, the public cry for help has been from the end of the first month to the seventh day or so.

On February 1, Hu Yifan went to the hospital canteen to donate 10 boxes of eggs. When we got to the door, we saw Kyushu's van unloading. It was a medical logistics company that helped the Wuhan Red Cross to process the donated materials. "

There are more trucks going to hospitals to deliver supplies, Hu said, and the number of hospitals that have issued appeals for help has dwindled. "after the grid of the community and the establishment of the Shelter Hospital, I feel the pressure on the hospital is not so great, " he said

"The biggest change this month has been the increasing standardization of disinfection and isolation measures and the installation of UV disinfection lamps everywhere, " said one nurse, adding that there were no UV lamps in the nurses' duty rooms, her department had experienced cases of tuberculosis among nurses. Now, not only ultraviolet disinfection equipment, but also air purifiers, washing machines and dryers, medical staff in the department can be timely cleaning clothes.

She was also impressed by two robots donated by a Tech Company. They have wheels, they can move around intelligently, they can call out automatically when they get to the door, they can pass things around instead of entering the ward manually, and they can reduce the possibility of cross infection.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Non-contact delivery robot donated to Kam Yin Tam Hospital. Photo courtesy of the respondents

On February 19, head nurse Yu of the outpatient department of the Jinyintan hospital told reporters that all kinds of materials in the hospital are sufficient for use at present. The hospital has recently received many batches of materials allocated by the state and donated by the society, and many urgently needed N95 masks and protective clothing have also been shipped, "I'm sure it will be fine for half a month. "

"Wuhan is still the Wuhan covered with Cherry Blossoms. "

Daily contact with critically ill patients can be stressful, but there are also moving out of the crack in the epidemic.

February 20 evening, just after the rainy season, in the gold and Silver Lake Hospital, the grass is gradually green, magpie calls can be heard everywhere. Apart from Birdsong, the only sound inside the compound came from two tall cryogenic liquid oxygen tanks. When the pressure is too high, the tank will automatically exhaust, issued a bare sound. In early February, Wisco's construction team built the 16-cubic-capacity central oxygen system in just five days. Without the new tanks, more than half of the hospital's patients would be without oxygen, a security guard said.

In front of the hospital's first aid station, a fully equipped ambulance stands open, ready to pick up and deliver patients. The driver who had just finished his lunch box was smoking a cigarette in the doorway, one of the few quiet moments of his day. The setting sun is reflected from the glass curtain wall of the building opposite the hospital and falls on the white ward upstairs.

On Feb. 22,31 provinces and the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps reported a cumulative 22,888 cured and discharged patients, according to data released by the NHRC. 21 provinces (autonomous regions and municipalities) increased by 0 percent. A spokesman for the National Health Commission said the number of confirmed cases in Wuhan, Hubei and other provinces was on a downward trend. It shows that with the strengthening of National Prevention and control measures and rescue forces, especially with the development of potential in Hubei Province and the continuous assistance of national counterpart medical forces, positive progress has been made in medical treatment, and the stock of confirmed cases is being rapidly digested.

On the evening of Feb. 22, a nurse sent a reporter a photo of the hallway outside the ward, with empty beds lined up in front of the window. "The extra beds that were prepared were not used, and the ward was empty a lot. There were fewer patients, and people were leaving the hospital every day, " she said, "One step at a time, it's easier to get to work. "

Compared with the outbreak of the disease, the current gold and silver pool of hospitals from the rush to stabilize. Chen Nian, a nurse, has gone from working more than a dozen hours a day to a steady eight. "Our ward has been relatively stable these two days. Only one patient has been admitted, and there are now empty beds. " The workload has decreased and the working hours have stabilized, but Chen Niannian still dare not relax. "there is no turning point in the epidemic, " he said. "The worst is yet to come. ".

Like Chen, after work, take off the protective clothing, Zhang Yanxia and Lin really life and ordinary people are no different.

Lin Zhenzhen usually like "happy fat house water. ". But the coke at the hospital commissary has been out of stock for over a month. Later, volunteers brought food and snacks to the staff, and Linzhenzhen shared several bottles of coke. Now, she only opens one when the weather is good and she is in a good mood.

At two in the morning, Zhang Chunyan and his colleagues got off work. The street lights dim at night, the whole road only a few medical staff in walking, the shadow of long and short. "I have seen so many lives leave since I started my career, and I hope you will cherish the moment. I believe that Wuhan will still be covered with cherry blossoms in the sky in no time, " Zhang wrote in her circle of friends

Lin Zhenzhen, Li Fei, Wu Na, Chen Nian
